{{more references|date=November 2017}} {{Infobox theatre | name = Lyceum Theatre | image = Lyceum Theatre NYC 2003.jpg | image_size = 200px | image_alt = | caption = Lyceum Theatre | image_map = | map_caption = | pushpin_map = | pushpin_map_caption= | address = 149 West [[45th Street (Manhattan)|45th Street]] | city = [[Manhattan]], New York City | country = United States | designation = | architect = [[Herts & Tallant]] | owner = [[The Shubert Organization]] | tenant = | operator = | capacity = 922 | type = | opened = November 2, 1903 | reopened = | yearsactive = | rebuilt = | closed = | demolished = | othernames = | production = ''[[The Play That Goes Wrong]]'' | currentuse = | website = [http://www.shubertorganization.com/theatres/lyceum.asp www.shubertorganization.com] }}
The '''Lyceum Theatre''' ({{IPAc-en|l|aɪ|ˈ|s|iː|ə|m}} {{respell|ly|SEE|əm}}) is a [[Broadway theatre]] located at 149 West [[45th Street (Manhattan)|45th Street]] near [[Times Square]] between [[Seventh Avenue (Manhattan)|Seventh]] and [[Sixth Avenue (Manhattan)|Sixth Avenue]] in [[Midtown Manhattan]], New York City.
==Overview== Opened in 1903, the Lyceum Theatre is one of the three oldest surviving Broadway venues (along with the [[Hudson Theatre|Hudson]] and [[New Amsterdam Theatre|New Amsterdam]] Theatres).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shubert.nyc/theatres/lyceum|title=Lyceum Theatre {{!}} Shubert Organization|website=www.shubert.nyc|access-date=2017-11-13}}</ref> It is the oldest continuously operating legitimate theatre in [[New York City]], and the first Broadway theatre ever to be granted landmark status (1974).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1978/05/17/archives/lyceum-declared-a-landmark.html|title=Lyceum Declared a Landmark|date=1978-05-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-11-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> It is one of the few theatres in New York which continues to operate under its original name.
Designed by architects [[Herts & Tallant]] in the [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts style]], the Lyceum was built by [[impresario]] [[Daniel Frohman]]. It opened on November 2, 1903, with the play ''The Proud Prince''. Frohman's brother [[Charles Frohman|Charles]] served as the theater's manager until his death in 1915.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nyc-architecture.com/MID/MID111.htm|title=New York Architecture Images- Lyceum Theater|website=nyc-architecture.com|access-date=2017-11-13}}</ref>
Two previous New York playhouses had also been called "Lyceum Theatre". The [[Fourteenth Street Theatre]] used the name from 1871 to 1879. Frohman's own [[Lyceum Theatre (New York City, 1885)|earlier Lyceum]] on [[Fourth Avenue (Manhattan)|Fourth Avenue]], was built in 1885 and closed in April 1902. It was replaced by the new Lyceum on 45th Street.
Among the prominent performers who appeared on the Lyceum's stage in its early years were [[Ethel Barrymore]], [[Fanny Brice]], [[Billie Burke]], [[Ina Claire]], [[Miriam Hopkins]], [[Walter Huston]], [[Basil Rathbone]], and [[Cornelia Otis Skinner]]. It has been owned by the [[Shubert Organization]] since 1952.<ref>{{Cite news| issn = 0362-4331| last = Zolotow| first = Sam| title = 'GOLDEN BOY' OPENS ON RIALTO TONIGHT; Revival of Clifford Odets Play at ANTA Playhouse -- John Garfield, Cobb in Cast| work = The New York Times| accessdate = 2018-10-19| date = 1952-03-12| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1952/03/12/archives/golden-boy-opens-on-rialto-tonight-revival-of-clifford-odets-play.html}}</ref>
The theatre maintains most of its original [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]] design, including its elaborate marble staircases and undulating marquee. Although it has three levels, it is one of the smaller Broadway theatres in terms of capacity, seating only 922. An apartment located above the orchestra, originally used by Frohman, is now the headquarters of the Shubert Archives.
