[[File:Canaletto (II) 002.jpg|thumb|350px|''Il ritorno del Bucintoro nel Molo il giorno dell'Ascensione'' (''The Return of the [[Bucentaur]] to the Molo on Ascension Day'', 1730) by [[Canaletto]] (1697–1768). Another painting of the same subject by Canaletto, ''Il Bucintoro al molo nel giorno dell'Ascensione'' (''The Bucentaur at the Molo on Ascension Day''), was purchased for £11.43&nbsp;million by a mystery bidder at a [[Christie's]] auction in London on 6 July 2005.<ref>{{citation|author=Sam Jones|title=Venetian painting by Canaletto sold for record £11.5m|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2005/jul/07/arts.artsnews|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130405011149/http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2005/jul/07/arts.artsnews|archivedate=5 April 2013|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=7 July 2005}}; {{citation|author=Dalya Alberge|title=Mystery bidder pays record £11m for classic Canaletto|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article541306.ece|newspaper=[[The Times]]|location=London|date=7 July 2005}}.</ref>]]
The '''Marriage of the Sea''' ({{lang-it|Sposalizio del Mare}}), sometimes referred to as the '''Marriage of the Adriatic''', was an ancient ceremony which used to symbolize the maritime dominion of Venice.
The ceremony, established in about 1000 AD to commemorate the Doge [[Pietro II Orseolo]]'s conquest of [[Dalmatia]], was originally one of [[supplication]] and placation, [[Ascension Day]] being chosen as that on which the doge set out on his expedition. The form it took was a solemn procession of boats, headed by the doge's ship (from 1311 the [[Bucentaur]]), out to sea by the [[Lido di Venezia|Lido]] port. A prayer was offered that "for us and all who sail thereon the sea may be calm and quiet", whereupon the doge and the others were solemnly [[Aspersion|aspersed]] with [[holy water]], the rest of which was thrown into the sea while the priests chanted "''Aspergēs mē hȳsōpō, et mundābor''" ("Sprinkle me with [[Ezov|hyssop]], and I will be clean" – [[Psalms|Psalm]] 51:7).<ref>The full verse appears in the [[New International Version]] of the [[Bible]] thus: "Cleanse me with hyssop, and I will be clean; / wash me, and I will be whiter than snow." (Psalm 51:7.)</ref>
To this ancient ceremony a quasi-[[sacrament]]al character was given by [[Pope Alexander III]] in 1177, in return for the services rendered by Venice in the struggle against the [[Holy Roman Emperor]] [[Frederick I, Holy Roman Emperor|Frederick I]]. The pope drew a ring from his finger and, giving it to the doge, bade him cast such a one into the sea each year on Ascension Day, and so wed the sea. Henceforth the ceremonial, instead of placatory and [[atonement in Christianity|expiatory]], became [[Wedding|nuptial]].
Every year the doge dropped a consecrated ring into the sea, and with the Latin words "''Desponsamus te, mare, in signum veri perpetuique domini''" ("We wed thee, sea, as a sign of true and everlasting domination"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Revised Latin Primer|last=Kennedy|first=Benjamin|publisher=Longmans|year=1962|isbn=|location=Great Britain|pages=19|chapter=35b|via=}}</ref>) declared Venice and the sea to be indissolubly one.<ref name="Festa della Sensa">{{citation|title=The Bucintoro|url=http://www.sevenonline.it/sensa/english/bucintorogb.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217015259/http://www.sevenonline.it/sensa/english/bucintorogb.htm|archivedate=17 February 2012|publisher=Comitato Festa della Sensa|accessdate=17 February 2012}}.</ref><ref name="Encyclopædia Britannica">{{citation|contribution=Bucentaur|contribution-url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/1911_Encyclop%C3%A6dia_Britannica/Bucentaur|editor=[[Hugh Chisholm]]|title=[[Encyclopædia Britannica Eleventh Edition|The Encyclopædia Britannica]]|edition=11th|location=Cambridge|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=1910–1911}}.</ref>
Despite the end of the office of the [[doge]] and the destruction of the Bucentaur, the ceremony of the marriage of the sea continues to this day. It is performed by the mayor of Venice aboard a smaller ceremonial barge called the ''Bissona Serenissima''.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}
