'''USS ''Newport News'' (SSN-750)''', a {{sclass-|Los Angeles|submarine}}, was the third ship of the [[United States Navy]] to be named for [[Newport News, Virginia]].
==Construction== The contract to build her was awarded to [[Northrop Grumman Newport News|Newport News Shipbuilding and Dry Dock Company]] in [[Newport News, Virginia]] on 19 April 1982 and her keel was laid down on 3 March 1984. She was [[ship naming and launching|launched]] on 15 March 1986 sponsored by [[Paul S. Trible, Jr.|Mrs. Rosemary D. Trible]], and [[ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 3 June 1989. Mayor [[Jessie M. Rattley]] presented the ship with a commemorative plaque containing the poem "Newport News," written by Newport News native Ronald W. Bell, whose poem "[[Hyman G. Rickover|Admiral Rickover]]" also appears upon a plaque aboard the ''Los Angeles'' class submarine {{USS|Hyman G. Rickover|SSN-709|2}}.Ref: Naval Submarine Base, Groton, Ct. The poem appears on this page with permission from the author:{{citation needed|date=February 2017}} ref: Sub Squadron 8, NOB, Norfolk
{{poemquote| ::"Newport News"
Harbor of a thousand ships Forger of a nation's fleet Gateway to the New World Where ocean and river meet Strength wrought from steel And a people's fortitude Such is the timeless legacy Of a place called Newport News.}}
==Initial operations== ''Newport News'' returned to [[Norfolk, Virginia]], following a six-month overseas deployment that included operations in the Middle East. In support of Operation Iraqi Freedom she launched 19 UGM-109C Tomahawk Land Attack Missiles in March 2003. She deployed in August 2004, first to take part in joint operations with allied navies in the North Atlantic, then to the U.S. Central Command area of operations "in support of national security interests and the global war on terrorism."{{Citation needed|date=May 2009}}
==Collision with Japanese ship== On 8 January 2007, ''Newport News'' was operating submerged in the [[Arabian Sea]] south of the [[Straits of Hormuz]] when it hit the Japanese tanker ''Mogamigawa''.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2007/WORLD/asiapcf/01/08/japan.us.ship/index.html U.S. sub collides with Japan ship], CNN, 8 January 2007.</ref> She had been operating as part of Carrier Strike Group 8 (CSG-8),<ref>[http://www.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=24919 Eisenhower Strike Group Completes JTFEX 06-2]</ref> organized around the [[aircraft carrier]] {{USS|Dwight D. Eisenhower|CVN-69|3}}. The Carrier Strike Group was redeploying to the Indian Ocean to support a maritime cordon during the [[War in Somalia (2006–2009)|war in Somalia]] when the incident happened.<ref name=US-STRIKE-IN-SOMALIA-TARGETS-AL-QAEDA-FIGURE>{{cite news |title=U.S. Strike in Somalia Targets Al-Qaeda Figure |work=The Washington Post |date=8 January 2007 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/01/08/AR2007010801822.html | first=Karen | last=DeYoung | accessdate=27 May 2010}}</ref> ''Newport News'' suffered damage to her bow, but there was no damage to the sail, mast or reactor, and she made for port in [[Bahrain]] under her own power.<ref name=NAVY-SUB-DAMAGED-IN-COLLISION-HEADS-FOR-PORT-IN-BAHRAIN>{{cite news |title=Navy sub damaged in collision heads for port in Bahrain |url=http://hamptonroads.com/node/205541 |last=Dorsey |first=Jack |date=9 January 2007 |work=[[The Virginian-Pilot]] |accessdate=11 January 2007 }}</ref> ''Newport News'' was escorted from the mouth of the Straits of Hormuz to Bahrain by the [[Guided Missile Destroyer]] {{USS|Benfold|DDG-65|2}}. This was due to the fact that the submarine was unable to transit submerged and has no surface defense capabilities. During the transit, Iranian aircraft and warships shadowed the ships. An official of the Kawasaki Kisen Company (or [[K Line]]), which owns the tanker, announced that ''Mogamigawa''{{'}}s hull and propellers were damaged.<ref>{{cite news |title=Japan's tanker sustains hull breach, propeller damage |url=http://www.itar-tass.com/eng/level2.html?NewsID=11146345&PageNum=0 |date=11 January 2007 |agency=[[Information Telegraph Agency of Russia]] |accessdate=11 January 2007}}</ref>
According to a Navy spokesman, the collision occurred as a result of the [[venturi effect]]. The tanker drove over the area where the submarine was submerged and this created a sucking effect that forced the submarine upward to the surface.<ref>{{cite news |title=Navy says speed of tanker sucked submarine up to surface |url=http://hamptonroads.com/node/205951 |last=Dorsey |first=Jack |date=10 July 2007 |work=[[The Virginian-Pilot]] |accessdate=11 January 2007}}</ref> The incident was the third collision between a U.S. nuclear-powered submarine and a Japanese civilian ship.<ref>{{cite news|author=Kiroku Hanai|title=U.S. presence vs. the public will|work=[[Japan Times]]|date=23 January 2007|url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/eo20070123kh.html}}</ref>
On 29 January, after the boat returned to Bahrain for repairs, administrative personnel actions ([[Admiral's Mast]]) were taken against several members of her crew, which included relieving the boat's commanding officer, Commander Matthew A. Weingart, of command due to a lack of confidence in his ability to command.<ref>{{cite news |title=USS Newport News Commanding Officer Relieved of Duty |url=http://www.wtkr.com/Global/story.asp?S=6005197&nav=ZolHbyvj |date=29 January 2007 |publisher=WTKR Newschannel 3 |accessdate=30 January 2007}}</ref>
On 10 April the Iranian [[Fars News Agency]] reported that ''Newport News'' has been leaking radioactive and chemical pollution in the Persian Gulf and claimed that following this formal complaint, the ship departed the gulf for a complete overhaul.<ref>{{cite news |title=US Submarine Forced to Leave Persian Gulf |url=http://english.farsnews.ir/newstext.php?nn=8601210568 |date=10 April 2007 |agency=FARS News Agency |accessdate=11 April 2007}} (Note that the image accompanying the FARS article is not a Los Angeles class submarine.)</ref> The [[United States Fifth Fleet|US Navy Fifth Fleet]] denied this claim restating that damage was limited to the bow and that the sail, mast and reactors were not damaged.<ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. withdraws damaged sub said by Iran to leak radiation into Gulf |url=http://www.worldtribune.com/worldtribune/07/front2454204.01875.html |date=13 April 2007 |work=World Tribune |accessdate=1 February 2008}}</ref> On 2 October 2007 the U.S. Navy agreed to pay [[K Line|Kawasaki Kisen Kaisha Ltd]], the company that owns ''Mogamigawa'' an undisclosed amount in compensation for the collision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20071003a9.html|agency=[[Kyodo News]]|title=U.S. Navy to pay for hitting tanker|work=[[Japan Times]]|date=3 October 2007}}</ref>
